libminer 0.0.0.9000
  • Reference

libminer

The goal of libminer is to . summarize the contents of your library.

Installation

You can install the development version of libminer from GitHub with:

# install.packages("devtools")
devtools::install_github("kateaurora/libminer")

Example

to get a count of installed packages in each of your library locations, use the lib_summary()

library(libminer)
## basic example code
lib_summary()
#>                                                                       Library
#> 1                                          C:/Program Files/R/R-4.4.1/library
#> 2                                                                C:/R_library
#> 3 C:/Users/McGivneyK/AppData/Local/Temp/1/RtmpeYYWYg/temp_libpath6408487c2225
#>   n_packages
#> 1         29
#> 2        402
#> 3          1

What is special about using README.Rmd instead of just README.md? You can include R chunks like so:

summary(cars)
#>      speed           dist       
#>  Min.   : 4.0   Min.   :  2.00  
#>  1st Qu.:12.0   1st Qu.: 26.00  
#>  Median :15.0   Median : 36.00  
#>  Mean   :15.4   Mean   : 42.98  
#>  3rd Qu.:19.0   3rd Qu.: 56.00  
#>  Max.   :25.0   Max.   :120.00

Youâ€™ll still need to render README.Rmd regularly, to keep README.md up-to-date. devtools::build_readme() is handy for this.

You can also embed plots, for example:

In that case, donâ€™t forget to commit and push the resulting figure files, so they display on GitHub and CRAN.
